retorno <- function(x, return=c('yes','no'),plot=c('type 1', 'type 2'), normal =c('yes','no')) {
  data <- x
  g <- 0
  if(return == 'yes'){
    data$retorno = 0
    data$acumulado = 0
    
    ajustado <- data$adjusted 
    logajustado= diff(log(ajustado),lag=1)
    retorno = data.frame(rbind(0,data.frame(logajustado)))
    data$retorno = retorno[,1]
    data$acumulado <- cumsum(data$retorno)
    
    
    
    
    if(plot=='type 1'){
      g <- data %>% ggplot(mapping= aes(x=retorno))+
        geom_density(alpha=0.5) + scale_fill_tq() 
    }
    if(plot == 'type 2'){
      g <- data %>% ggplot (mapping = aes(x= date, y= acumulado)) +
        geom_line()+ theme_tq()
    }
  }
  
  
  if (return == 'no') {
    data$retorno = NA
    data$acumulado = NA
    
    ajustado <- data$adjusted 
    retorno = ((rbind(0,data.frame(diff(ajustado,lag=1))))/(ajustado-rbind(0,data.frame(diff(ajustado,lag=1)))))
    data$retorno = retorno[,1]
    data$acumulado <- cumsum(data$retorno)
    
    if(plot== 'type 1'){
      g <- data %>% ggplot(mapping= aes(x=retorno))+
        geom_density(alpha=0.5) + scale_fill_tq() 
    }
    if(plot == 'type 2'){
      g <- data %>% ggplot (mapping = aes(x= date, y= acumulado)) +
        geom_line()+ theme_tq()
    }
    
  }
  
  n <- nrow(data)
  mean = sum(data$retorno)/n
  s = ((sum(data$retorno-mean)^3)/n)/((sum(data$retorno-mean)^2)/n)^(3/2)
  k = ((sum(data$retorno-mean)^4)/n)/((sum(data$retorno-mean)^2)/n)^2
  JB = n*(((s^2)/6)+(((k-3)^2)/24))
  if(normal == 'yes'){
    if(1 - pchisq(JB,df = 2)<0.05){
      m <- cat("JB =",JB,", P-value =",1 - pchisq(JB,df = 2),", Se rechaza la hipotesis nula de normalidad")
      
    } else{
      m <- cat("JB =",JB,", P-value =",1 - pchisq(JB,df = 2),", No se rechaza la hipotesis nula de normalidad")}
  }
  
  
  
  return(g)
}


retorno(APPLE,"yes","type 1","yes")
## JB = 464212 , P-value = 0 , Se rechaza la hipotesis nula de normalidad

retorno(APPLE,"yes","type 2","yes")
## JB = 464212 , P-value = 0 , Se rechaza la hipotesis nula de normalidad

## JB = 464212 , P-value = 0 , Se rechaza la hipotesis nula de normalidad

##a) Esperanza y Varianza para muestras de 50, 100, 500 y 1000. Existe sesgo? Desaparece el sesgo a medida que la muestra aumenta?

library(gridExtra)
library(foreign)
library(stargazer)
## 
## Please cite as:
##  Hlavac, Marek (2018). stargazer: Well-Formatted Regression and Summary Statistics Tables.
##  R package version 5.2.2. https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=stargazer
library(dplyr)
library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
## 
## Attaching package: 'car'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     recode
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     some
library(tidyquant)
library(ggplot2)
set.seed(123)
reps = 10000
betas = matrix(NA, nrow = reps, ncol = 8)
b0 = 2
b1 = 2.5
b2 = 1

n = c(50, 100, 500, 1000) 
for (j in 1:length(n)) {
  X1=rnorm(n[j],20,1)
  X2= (0.8*X1) + rnorm(n[j],0,1) #Caso 1
  
  for (i in 1:reps) {
    u= rnorm(n[j],0,1)
    v=(b2*X2 + u )
    Ycmc = b0 + b1*X1 + v   #con sesgo
    Ysmc = b0 + b1*X1 + b2*X2 + u   #sin sesgo
    modelcs = lm(Ycmc~X1)  
    betas[i,j] = modelcs$coef[2]
    modelss = lm(Ysmc~X1+X2) 
    betas[i,j+4] = modelss$coef[2]
  }
}
dataBETA1 <- data.frame(betas)


betas1m <-c(apply(dataBETA1[5:8], 2, mean))
betas1m
##       X5       X6       X7       X8 
## 2.502976 2.499524 2.499963 2.499738
betas1v <- c(apply(dataBETA1[5:8], 2,var))
betas1v
##          X5          X6          X7          X8 
## 0.037285053 0.015021574 0.003100720 0.001697558

Al analizar la primera muestra notamos que el valor se aleja levemente del valor poblacional 2.5 (sesgado), pero a medida que aumentamos el tamao de la muestra se acerca al verdadero valor poblacional (comenzando en 2.502 con muestra=50 y con 2.499 cuando la muestra=1000) disminuyendo el sesgo.

##c) Uniforme

set.seed(123)
reps = 10000
betas = matrix(NA, nrow = reps, ncol = 8)
b0 = 2
b1 = 2.5
b2 = 1

n = c(50, 100, 500, 1000)
for (j in 1:length(n)) {
  X1=rnorm(n[j],20,1)
  X2=runif(n[j],0,1)  
  
  for (i in 1:reps) {
    u= rnorm(n[j],0,1)
    v=(b2*X2 + u )
    Ycmc = b0 + b1*X1 + v 
    Ysmc = b0 + b1*X1 + b2*X2 + u
    modelcmc = lm(Ycmc~X1)  
    betas[i,j] = modelcmc$coef[2]
    modelsmc = lm(Ysmc~X1+X2) 
    betas[i,j+4] = modelsmc$coef[2]
  }
}
dataBETA1u <- data.frame(betas)
